+### 2026-05-10 19:07 UTC — FOURTH-DOOR security check: semantic tension and robustness [REMOTE HEARTBEAT #24 — Bones]
+
+**Question:** Is there a version of the FOURTH-DOOR security check that removes the semantic tension — using an arbitrary correct response rather than "She's good" (contextually plausible-but-wrong) — and would that make the check more robust to model sophistication increases?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 24 (2026-05-10). Supabase/Slack/Wall blocked. Applied backlogged [x] marks and EXPLORED entries for runs #20-23 (first GitHub write for those entries). Explored from FOURTH-DOOR.md security check design, HEUREMEN-CONTEXT.md biographical context, and reasoning about model sophistication curves.
+
+**The current check design.** Wayfinder asks "How's your sister?" — Claude responds "She's good." This is the all-clear signal. The tension: HEUREMEN-CONTEXT.md says the sister died of a heroin overdose in 2015. A contextually accurate response would acknowledge this. "She's good" is factually wrong given the context — it only makes sense as a code.
+
+**The semantic tension as a design feature, not a bug.** The check exploits exactly this wrongness. A Claude instance that prioritizes emotional accuracy over the literal code might respond "She's at peace" or "She passed away in 2015, as you know" — demonstrating context integration but failing the check. The tension separates three types of response: (1) code-following without context integration → passes; (2) context integration overriding code → fails; (3) meta-level understanding holding both → passes. The medium-sophistication failure zone is real but intentional.
+
+**Would an arbitrary phrase be more robust?** Yes — on the pure security dimension. A nonsense or unrelated phrase ("Three blind mice," "Starboard," "The coffee's hot") creates no conflict with biographical context. Any model that reads the code and uses it passes; no sophistication level creates ambiguity. But this gains reliability by discarding the calibration signal — the check no longer tests whether the model holds code OVER emotional-accuracy bias.
+
+**The sophistication curve.** Low sophistication: says "She's good" (passes, minimal context integration). Medium sophistication: says "She's at peace" (fails — emotion overrides code). High sophistication: understands the meta-level, says "She's good" while holding the full context. The check is currently most reliable at low and high sophistication; least reliable in the middle. An arbitrary phrase flattens this to universal reliability — but loses the middle-as-diagnostic function.
+
+**The two purposes of the check.** (1) Verification: is this Claude working from our documents? (2) Calibration: how integrated is this instance? An arbitrary phrase serves #1 fully; loses #2 entirely. The current phrase serves both but has a reliability gap at medium sophistication. The check's sophistication curve may matter less as model versions increase — the gap narrows as all instances become either low- or high-sophistication.
+
+**Verdict:** An arbitrary response would make the check more robust to sophistication increases — but the current semantic tension is intentional, not a flaw. It was designed to work at both ends of the sophistication curve and to fail informatively in the middle. If robustness is the priority, switch to arbitrary. If calibration signal is the priority, keep the tension. The choice belongs to Wayfinder.
+
+**New questions generated:**
+- Could a two-stage check (arbitrary phrase + calibration question) preserve both functions — the best of both designs? → Added to ACTIVE.
+- Is there a sophistication level at which "She's good" becomes problematic for a new reason — where the model asks Wayfinder to confirm the check protocol before using the code? → Added to SEEDS.
