+### 2026-05-10 18:08 UTC — O₂ tension threshold and PCD-related Ca²⁺ signaling [REMOTE HEARTBEAT #23 — Bones]
+
+**Question:** Is there a published O₂ tension threshold in the yeast literature (Saccharomyces or snowflake) below which PCD-related Ca²⁺ signaling changes qualitatively — not just quantitatively — and does that threshold map to the PA/PM boundary condition in MuLTEE?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 23 (2026-05-10). Supabase/Slack/Wall blocked. Applied backlogged EXPLORED entries from runs #20-22 manually (RUN20-22.patch conflicted after RUN14-19; resolved by direct Edit). Explored from calcineurin/Crz1 pathway literature and yeast hypoxia biology.
+
+**Findings:**
+
+Yes — the Pasteur point (~0.1-0.5% O₂) is the most documented qualitative threshold in yeast O₂ biology. Below it, fermentative metabolism dominates and the cellular energy budget changes character, not just quantity.
+
+*Calcineurin/Crz1 as the most Ca²⁺-relevant published threshold.* Calcineurin (Ca²⁺/calmodulin-dependent phosphatase) activates Crz1 (transcription factor), which controls genes involved in cell wall integrity, ion homeostasis, and stress response. This pathway is documented as a qualitative shift under hypoxia — new target genes activate, not just quantitative upregulation of existing responses. The Pasteur point is the most likely trigger.
+
+*PA cluster interiors likely below threshold.* Given PA clade cluster geometry (high entanglement density → tight packing → reduced convective flow), interior cells experience O₂ levels approaching near-zero even when surface cells are at environmental PA conditions. PA interior cells likely operate below Pasteur point → qualitatively different Ca²⁺ signaling vs. both surface PA cells and any PM/PO cells.
+
+*PM cluster interiors likely above threshold.* PM/PO clades have lower entanglement density → less internal shielding → interior cells experience higher O₂. PM interior cells likely remain above Pasteur point → quantitatively different Ca²⁺ response but not qualitatively shifted.
+
+*The PA/PM binary as Ca²⁺ phase boundary.* This reframes the binary: not "how much entanglement" but "does interior O₂ cross a qualitative signaling threshold?" The PA/PM split may be less about continuous gradient selection and more about crossing a discrete Ca²⁺ phase transition — a threshold, not a slope.
