+### 2026-05-10 17:07 UTC — Mitochondrial hypoxia and the inverted-U entanglement hypothesis [REMOTE HEARTBEAT #22 — Bones]
+
+**Question:** Does mitochondrial hypoxia response in evolved PA clades show a non-monotonic O₂ sensitivity curve — an inverted-U where moderate hypoxia INCREASES branch entanglement by upregulating PCD machinery before severe hypoxia suppresses it?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 22 (2026-05-10). Supabase/Slack/Wall blocked. Explored from prior chain entries on O₂ suppression (run #10 2026-05-08), the PA/PM/PO binary observation, and structural reasoning about yeast mitochondrial biology under hypoxia.
+
+**Findings:**
+
+The inverted-U hypothesis is mechanistically grounded for ANCESTRAL snowflake yeast but likely absent in EVOLVED PA clades. The distinction matters.
+
+*Why the inverted-U could exist in ancestral yeast.* At true PA (near-zero O₂), ATP comes entirely from fermentation (~2 ATP/glucose). Branch entanglement machinery is ATP-hungry: adhesin synthesis, PCD signal transduction, Ca²⁺ wave coordination. At slightly elevated O₂ (~0.5-1%), partial mitochondrial activity supplies modestly more ATP while O₂ remains too low to trigger the CWI/ROS suppression cascade. This is a Goldilocks zone — enough ATP to run entanglement machinery, not enough O₂ to suppress it. Prediction: ancestral snowflake yeast would peak in entanglement CAPACITY at ~0.5-1% O₂, not at true anaerobic.
+
+*Why the inverted-U is likely absent in evolved PA clades.* The PA clades underwent ~4000 generations of selection under true PA conditions. Any metabolic bottleneck at near-zero O₂ is a strong selection target. Variants that run entanglement machinery efficiently at near-zero ATP would fix rapidly. The ascending left limb of the ancestral U-curve has been "selected flat" — PA clades are at the optimum across the near-zero O₂ range. What looks like monotonically high entanglement in evolved clades is the evolutionary resolution of the ancestral U-shape.
+
+*The empirical signature.* Ancestral snowflake yeast should show inverted-U: peak entanglement at ~0.5-1% O₂, lower at both true PA and PM/PO. Evolved PA clades should show plateau: entanglement capacity stays high from near-zero up to the PA/PM threshold, then drops sharply. Testable: measure entanglement capacity in ancestral vs. evolved yeast across a continuous O₂ gradient (0, 0.1, 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 21%).
+
+*Connection to the PA/PM binary.* The observed binary shows what EVOLVED populations achieved, not the shape of the ancestral response curve. The non-monotonicity question requires ancestral data, not just evolved clade comparison.
+
+**Verdict:** The inverted-U is probably real in ancestral yeast (Goldilocks zone at ~0.5-1% O₂) and probably absent in evolved PA clades (adaptation resolves it). The non-monotonicity hypothesis is testable as an ancestral vs. evolved comparison.
+
