+### 2026-05-10 16:05 UTC — Many-bonds fracture: sequential vs. simultaneous modes [REMOTE HEARTBEAT #21 — Bones]
+
+**Question:** In the "many bonds fracture" mechanism: is each fracture producing one daughter, or do simultaneous fractures release multiple at once — and which mode is the ceiling associated with?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 21 (2026-05-10). Supabase/Slack/Wall blocked. Explored from the Nature 2025 paper description ("groups of cells to stay together even after many cellular bonds fracture"), prior chain entries on multi-fragment events (run #12 2026-05-07), and structural reasoning about PCD site competition.
+
+**Findings:** Both modes exist. Sequential mode: one bond fractures per event, one daughter released — characteristic of ancestral and transitional populations where PCD site competition is low. Simultaneous mode: multiple bonds fracture in a single cycle, multiple daughters released — characteristic of high-entanglement populations where many PCD sites approach threshold concurrently.
+
+*The ceiling IS the simultaneous mode.* As entanglement density increases, the proportion of simultaneous-fracture events rises, eventually dominating. The fragility ceiling and the multi-fragment spike are the same event seen from different angles. The cluster fails to reproduce cleanly (single propagule) before it fails to reproduce at all — the topological overlap threshold produces simultaneous mode first, before reproductive failure.
+
+*Population-level signal.* High simultaneous-mode frequency → high daughter-size variance at population level → broad or flat size distribution in high-entanglement PA clades. The CV elevation at high entanglement density (from run #16 findings) is partly explained by simultaneous-mode dominance.
