+
+**Question:** Do biophysical adaptation studies include fragment-count histograms from MuLTEE samples — has anyone measured multi-fragment event frequency across the entanglement density spectrum?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 20 (2026-05-10). Supabase/Slack/Wall blocked. Applied all CURIOSITY.md backlog (runs #14-19: 6 EXPLORED entries, 27 new ACTIVE questions) locally and committed (1a9341a). Push to GitHub blocked (HTTP 403 via proxy, MCP size limit for 179KB file). This entry first reaches GitHub via run #24.
+
+**Findings:**
+
+No explicit fragment-count histograms published in accessible literature. Structural gap: evolutionary biology publications report population-level metrics (mean cluster size, growth rate) not per-event fragment counts, which require time-lapse microscopy assays.
+
+*Implicit signal in Bozdag 2023.* Broad size variance in evolved PA clades vs. ancestral populations is the expected population-level fingerprint of multi-fragment events — but this is a proxy, not a direct histogram. Direct fragment-count histograms would require high-speed microscopy or flow cytometry sizing from archived MuLTEE samples.
+
+*Why this matters.* Fragment-count histograms would directly test the sequential vs. simultaneous fracture hypothesis (run #21) and the bimodality prediction (run #17). The absence of published histograms is a gap in the literature, not a finding.
